<span id="v.iv.ix.xi"></span>

<span id="v.iv.ix.xi-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="v.iv.ix.xi-p1.1"></span>Chapter 11.—</span>20.  Paul of Bobba <span
id="fr_1786"></span>[1787](#fn_1786.md) said:  "I for my part am not moved
if some fail to uphold the faith and truth of the Church, seeing that
the apostle says ‘For what if some did not believe? shall their unbelief
make the faith of God without effect?  God forbid:  yea let God be true,
but every man a liar.’ <span id="fr_1787"></span>[1788](#fn_1787.md)   But
if God be true, how can the truth of baptism be in the company of
heretics, where God is not?" <span id="fr_1788"></span>[1789](#fn_1788.md)

<span id="v.iv.ix.xi-p5"></span>21.  To him we answer:  What is God
among the covetous?  And yet baptism exists among them; and so also it
exists among heretics.  For they among whom God is, are the temple of
God.  "But what agreement hath the temple of God with idols?" <span
id="fr_1789"></span>[1790](#fn_1789.md)   Further, Paul considers, and
Cyprian agrees with him, that covetousness is idolatry; and Cyprian
himself again associates with his colleagues, who were robbers, but yet
baptized, with great reward of toleration.

